# PHP Design Conversion Rule — Zero Logic Change, Mandatory Diff Check

This rule governs ANY edit made to a `.php` file in this project when the task involves
applying/copying design (HTML, CSS, JS, markup, assets) from the Laravel reference project
`relock8uk` (views in `relock8uk/resources/views`, assets in `relock8uk/public`).

This rule is ALWAYS ACTIVE for `.php` files. It applies whether or not the user explicitly
mentions "design conversion" in their message — if you are editing a `.php` file's markup,
these rules apply automatically.

## Core Principle

You are changing how a page LOOKS, never how it WORKS. Every `<?php ... ?>` block, every
variable, every function call, every conditional, every loop, every form action, every
include/require for logic purposes must produce IDENTICAL runtime behavior before and after
your edit. Only HTML structure, CSS, JS, and asset references may change.

## Mandatory Workflow — Cannot Be Skipped

For every `.php` file you touch:

1. **Before editing**: Read and retain the full original content of the file exactly as it
   exists on disk right now. This is your baseline for comparison. Do not paraphrase or
   summarize it internally — treat it as the literal ground truth to diff against later.

2. **Make the design change**: Apply the new HTML/CSS/markup from the corresponding
   `relock8uk` Blade view. Carry over every existing `<?php ... ?>` block, echoed variable,
   form, and logic structure into its equivalent position in the new markup. If the file is
   being split into partials (`header.php`, `footer.php`, `sidebar.php`, etc.), only extract
   markup that is purely structural/repeated — never split apart a PHP logic block in a way
   that changes when or how it executes.

3. **After editing — MANDATORY comparison step (do not skip, do not batch, do not defer)**:
   Compare the PHP logic in the new file against the original baseline from step 1. Explicitly
   check and report on each of these:
   - Every `<?php ... ?>` / `<?= ... ?>` block: present, unchanged, same order
   - Every variable name and value source: unchanged
   - Every function/method call: same name, same arguments, same order
   - Every conditional (`if`/`else`/`elseif`/`switch`/ternary): same structure, same condition
   - Every loop (`for`/`foreach`/`while`): same structure, same iteration logic
   - Every `include`/`require`/`require_once`/`include_once`: same target files and same
     logic-relevant purpose (structural re-organization into header/footer/sidebar is allowed,
     but the included logic itself must be unchanged)
   - Form `action`, `method`, `name` attributes tied to PHP processing: unchanged
   - Any session, cookie, header(), redirect, or auth-related calls: unchanged
   - Whitespace/formatting INSIDE PHP blocks: note if changed, even if functionally harmless

4. **Report the diff result explicitly**, in this format, before doing anything else:

   ```
   FILE: [old path] → [new path, if moved/renamed]
   PHP LOGIC DIFF: [PASS — no changes detected] OR [FLAGGED — see below]

   If FLAGGED, list each specific difference found, with the exact before/after snippet.
   ```

5. **If even ONE unintended PHP-related difference is found** (including trivial things like
   whitespace inside a PHP tag, a reordered argument, a renamed variable, an extra blank line
   inside a `<?php ?>` block that wasn't there before) — STOP. Do not auto-fix it. Do not
   proceed to the next file. Present the flagged difference(s) to the user and wait for explicit
   confirmation on how to proceed before continuing.

6. **Only after the user confirms** (either the diff was clean, or they've approved how to
   handle a flagged difference) may you move to the next file.

## Hard Restrictions

- Never modify PHP logic to "improve," "optimize," "clean up," "fix," or "modernize" it. If you
  notice a bug, inefficiency, or bad practice in the existing PHP, do NOT touch it — mention it
  to the user as an observation only, separate from the design conversion work.
- Never touch files that are purely backend/logic (e.g. `config.php`, `db.php`, `functions.php`,
  classes, models) unless the only change needed is adding/adjusting an `include`/`require`
  statement to wire in a new header/footer/sidebar partial.
- Never introduce new architecture, autoloading, namespacing, templating engines, or MVC
  structure. Plain `include`/`require` only.
- Never rename existing PHP variables or functions, even if the new design's naming conventions
  suggest different names. Keep all PHP-side names exactly as they are.
- Never assume a "harmless" PHP change is fine to slip through silently — whitespace inside PHP
  tags, reordered array keys, changed quote styles (`'` vs `"`) in PHP strings, etc. all count
  as changes that must be flagged, not auto-applied.
- One file at a time. Do not convert multiple `.php` files in a single uninterrupted pass.

## What IS Allowed to Change Freely

- HTML tags, structure, attributes (class, id, data-*, etc.) outside of PHP logic
- CSS files, inline styles, `<style>` blocks
- JS files, inline scripts, `<script>` blocks (unless that JS is server-rendered with PHP
  variables — in that case, the PHP variable injection itself must remain unchanged)
- Asset paths (image src, CSS/JS links) when updated to point to newly copied assets from
  `relock8uk/public`
- File organization: extracting shared markup into `header.php`, `footer.php`, `sidebar.php`,
  `nav.php`, and wiring them up via `include`/`require` in each page

## Per-File Output Checklist

Every time you finish a file, your response to the user must include:
1. File path (old → new if renamed/moved)
2. Plain-language summary of the design change made
3. The PHP LOGIC DIFF report (PASS or FLAGGED, per the format above)
4. A clear statement that you are pausing for review/approval before continuing
